<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Johnny’s Is the Best Overall Choice</h2>

  <p>
    Johnny’s Selected Seeds stands out because it makes maturity timing easy to work with.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is especially useful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>comparing early and late varieties of the same crop</li>
    <li>identifying crops that fit within tight windows</li>
    <li>building a plan around what can realistically mature</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This allows you to plan with confidence instead of hoping crops will finish in time.
  </p>

  <p>
    That clarity is essential when you need to understand <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">whether a crop will mature before your first frost</a>, especially in shorter growing seasons.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why West Coast Seeds Works Well for Short Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    West Coast Seeds is a strong option when your growing season is limited by both time and temperature.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its catalog tends to include:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>varieties suited to cooler conditions</li>
    <li>crops that perform with less heat</li>
    <li>reliable options for shorter growing windows</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This makes it easier to choose crops that will grow steadily instead of stalling mid-season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why High Mowing Is a Strong Alternative</h2>

  <p>
    High Mowing Organic Seeds works well when conditions are less predictable.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its varieties tend to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>perform consistently across different seasons</li>
    <li>handle variability in temperature and weather</li>
    <li>focus on practical, productive crops</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This makes it a good choice when your growing window varies from year to year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Matters in a Short Season Garden</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Fast maturity.</strong> Crops need to finish within a limited timeframe.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable growth.</strong> Plants need to develop steadily even when conditions are not ideal.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good crop selection.</strong> Some crops are simply better suited to shorter seasons than others.
  </p>

  <p>
    These factors determine whether you get a harvest at all.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Short Season Gardens Fail</h2>

  <p>
    Most problems come from choosing crops that take too long.
  </p>

  <p>
    This leads to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>plants that never reach maturity</li>
    <li>late harvests that get cut off by weather</li>
    <li>wasted space late in the season</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These issues are often not obvious until it is too late to fix them.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why it helps to prioritize <a href="/guides/best-seed-company-for-fast-maturing-varieties/">fast-maturing varieties</a> that are more likely to finish within your available window.
  </p>
</section>

